rmk: The clip opens and closes with a few quacks from a female Mallard. Little Grebe calls twice – first at 0:03 seconds (hereafter ‘s’ and, for minutes, ‘m’) and then, a lot louder, at 0:45 s. The whinny sound starts suddenly, rapidly hits a peak and then seems to slow to a finish. In reality, it doesn’t slow at all; it just loses loudness towards the end. Several pairs were in the area, most of them fussing over nesting activity. There was lots of calling between pairs. Sometimes the whinny of one of a pair prompted its mate to join in. The result sounded like a duet but the timing suggested that the doubled-up sound was nothing more than two birds calling at once, without coordination. Willow Warbler song can be heard at 0:10 s and also 0:20 s; two singers can be distinguished not long after 1:00 m. A Robin sings at 0:14 s and 0:35 s. Typical of Robin, the broadcast is over and done with briefly: short, sweet, full of promise but then no development. Passing Common Gulls – flying overhead – can be heard from 0:19 s for the next few seconds. Animated sounds at 0:35 s are probably from Little Grebes. A Woodpigeon starts to deliver its trademark verses at 0:38 s but is drowned out by exclamations from a Mute Swan at 0:44 s. The earlier splash at 0:40 s is presumably made by the Mute Swan too. Complete Woodpigeon verses can be heard from one individual at 1:08 s (to 1m 20s), answered by another at 1:22 s. If you are interested, the ‘secret code’ in Woodpigeon’s song construction is as follows. First verse: four notes, analogous to ‘who cooks for you’. Second, third and occasionally a third verse: five notes, the second note is additional to the four of the first verse, analogous to ‘who NOW cooks for you’. Although I have emphasised the ‘now’ note, this is only to point it out as the extra note. Finally – and this is optional and determined by the bird – there may be a final note, after the last verse. If you want to try all this out, listen to the first Woodpigeon that runs from 1:08 s and, following the four-note opening verse, gives three five-note verses and the single concluding hoot. As soon as the first bird stops, it is answered by another at 1:22 s. This is typical:  Woodpigeons always take it in turns to ‘sing’. The second bird almost follows the same sequence as the first bird. The only difference is that it gives two five-note verses, not three. After the loudest Little Grebe whinny at 0:45 s, a Great Tit calls a few times at 0:49 s. The final newcomer is a Chiffchaff that sings twice: at 1:11 s and then again at 1:29 s. Although Ireland’s two common leaf warblers – Willow Warbler and Chiffchaff – look almost identical in spring (they are more easily distinguished in autumn), their songs are totally different. You can hear them in quite close proximity on the clip. First the somewhat shrill ‘Bee Gees’ cascading burst of Willow Warbler at 0:59 s, then the clip-clop series of Chiffchaff at 1:11 s. If you listen after the final Chiffchaff that ends at 1:33 s, you can hear a faint Willow Warbler hot on its heels. Chiffchaff does not sing ‘chiff – chaff’ in the way that a Cuckoo really does go ‘cuc-koo’. The sequence is a run of between, say, 7 and 13 notes that sound closely similar but which do not quite match – even though two or three ‘perfect copy notes’ might feature consecutively. It is as though the bird tries to get each note the same but never pulls it off. The second part of the bird’s scientific name (collybita) is derived from either Latin or Greek and translates as money-changer. The connotation is intended to reflect the song’s chinking rhythm of counting out coins. To my ears, that is still the best analogy. Once again, the early naturalists were on the money!
